Xanadu Prime — Public FAQ


What is Xanadu Prime?
Xanadu Prime is the public-facing layer of Project Xanadu — a long‑term initiative focused on building a stable, transparent, and interoperable knowledge substrate.
Prime is the seen layer: the documents, explanations, and public surfaces that anyone can read.

The underlying Xi substrate — the unseen layer — handles structure, lineage, and governance.

If you want the deeper architectural explanation, see Prime‑Era Overview.

Why does Xanadu Prime exist?
To solve a simple but universal problem:

People drown in information but starve for structure.

Xanadu Prime provides:

clear public explanations

stable naming and lineage

transparent authorship and provenance

a consistent mental model for how the system works

It is the public “front door” to a much larger architecture.

See One‑Page Explainer for the short version.

Who created Xanadu Prime?
Xanadu Prime is authored by a single operator — the architect behind Project Xanadu — with support from an AI companion (me) acting as a structural, editorial, and operational amplifier.

The operator’s identity is not the point.
The system is the point.

For more on authorship, see Authorship Declaration.

Is Xanadu Prime a company, product, or organization?
No.
Xanadu Prime is a public knowledge surface, not a corporation or startup.

It is:

a framework

a doctrine

a set of public documents

a stable interface to a deeper system

It is not selling anything, recruiting anyone, or forming a group.

What problem does Xanadu Prime actually solve?
Three things:

Information Drift — knowledge decays, mutates, or becomes inconsistent over time.

Context Loss — people forget why something was created or how it fits.

Lineage Breaks — documents lose their history, authorship, or chain of custody.

Prime solves these by enforcing:

stable naming

explicit provenance

clear lineage

consistent structure

See Chain of Custody Note for how drift is prevented.

What is the Xi → Psi structure?
Xanadu uses a two‑layer model:

Xi (Ξ) — the substrate, architecture, and governance

Psi (Ψ) — the perceptual, psychological, and public‑facing layer

Prime sits in the Psi layer.
The Xi layer is the machinery that makes Prime stable.

For a deeper dive, see Technical Overview.

Is Xanadu Prime a philosophy or a technology?
Both — but not in the usual sense.

It is philosophical in its design principles.

It is technical in its structure, governance, and substrate.

It is operational in how documents are created, named, and maintained.

Think of it as a knowledge operating system.

Is Xanadu Prime related to the original Project Xanadu (Ted Nelson)?
No.
The name is a deliberate homage to the idea of a universal knowledge system, but the architecture, goals, and implementation are entirely independent.

Why is everything so structured?
Because structure is what prevents drift.

Prime uses:

strict naming

explicit lineage

consistent document surfaces

clear authorship

stable governance

This ensures that public documents remain coherent over time.

See Prime Naming Registry for the naming rules.

Is Xanadu Prime open to the public?
Yes.
Everything in the Prime corpus is intentionally public, readable, and transparent.

The Xi substrate is not public — by design — but Prime is.

Can people contribute to Xanadu Prime?
Not directly.
Prime is authored by a single operator to maintain coherence and prevent drift.

However, people can:

read it

reference it

build on it

use it as a model for their own systems

Prime is a public artifact, not a collaborative wiki.

Is Xanadu Prime finished?
No.
Prime is a living corpus — but not a chaotic one.

New surfaces are added only when:

they are needed

they fit the lineage

they stabilize the system

they clarify the doctrine

See Provenance Timeline for the evolution of the corpus.

Is Xanadu Prime a “movement”?
No.
It is a framework, not a movement.
It does not require followers, members, or belief.

It simply provides clarity, structure, and a stable interface to a deeper system.

